 upon barriers to play that exist beyond the minds and bodies of individual children, within a 'disabling' environment. Barriers include those associated with the design of the built environment, social attitudes and professional practices. The report maps an agenda for further research in this area, emphasising the need for participatory methodologies that capture the views and voices of children with disabilities, their friends and families, on this important issue of play. ABSTRACTING & INDEXING Barriers to Play and Recreation for Children and Young People with Disabilities is covered by the following services: Baidu Scholar DOAB (Directory of Open Access Books) EBSCO Discovery Service Google Scholar J-Gate Naviga (Softweco) Primo Central (ExLibris) ReadCube Semantic Scholar Summon (ProQuest) TDOne (TDNet) WorldCat (OCLC)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / People with Disabilities.2bisacsh  aAccessibility.  aBarriers.  aDisability.  aExclusion.  aInequality.  aPlay.  aRights.  aSocial Attitudes.  aUseability.1 aBeckett, Angharad, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCannon Jones, Nan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCoussens, Marieke, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDesoete, Annemie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aFenney Salkeld, Deborah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLynch, Helen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPrellwitz, Maria, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut0 cEPUBz97831105262190 cprintz9783